<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un2040d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2040">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un2all.htm#un2040d"> (VI.D.7) 40(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Water supply</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In early times, and indeed so long as galvanised iron tanks remained unknown, the <mark>water-supply</mark> was a vital question for all navigation. Only a poor supply could be carried in the heavy earthenware jars on which the Greeks depended; and so it was that a delay of even two or three days, wind-bound on a coast where the water-supply was in hostile hands, was a matter of life and death. <small> Walter Leaf, <a name="WLAS" href="/udra/udex.htm#WLAS"><cite title="source">Troy: A Study in Homeric Geography</cite></a> (1912), 262</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c16267e" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16267e">VI.C.16:267(e)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
